    {
      "id": "c6bbe6979892851514caa7a753bb3b68abfffe93",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2019-03-15 11:22:34.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nIsn't this a sign that other monitoring tools may break?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "9fe94e589360d5615066db3bb70067700d558178",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2019-03-15 11:24:47.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAlso, if we don't think the output format change is a problem, this change should be merged into the patch that broke the test.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e2c894dba1cf136db8cd9035a892d17bcffc097e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 308,
        "name": "Amir Shehata",
        "email": "ashehata@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "ashehata"
      },
      "date": "2019-03-15 18:58:10.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI can merge it. The changes in MR routing do imply that some monitoring tools might need to be updated. Do we need to maintain backwards compatibility for this? If so I can keep the format of the file the same, but the obsolete entries are just going to be unused.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "7ba40c26618fbefcc99800cad54d6ba0c856cae9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2019-03-15 22:47:03.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nIt would be at least useful to post to lustre-devel and some power users like Joe (IML), Stephane and Li Xi (DDN), LLNL (LMT), James S. (ORNL), and whomever at Cray that Patrick recommends, to get an idea if these router stats are used by external tools.\n\nIt may be that nobody has monitored the routers in this way, and you are free & clear, but if it isn't too much work it is better to avoid breaking the stats output if possible.\n\nThere has been a bunch of renaming of stats files, but that is relatively easy to handle (totally transparent if using lctl or equivalent API) vs. changing the content/parsers.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
